# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hardhat
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Ethereum was conceived in 2013 by programmer Vitalik Buterin.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Other founders include Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, Anthony Di Iorio, and Joseph Lubin.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In 2014, development work began and was crowdfunded, and the network went live on 30 July 2015.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Ethereum allows anyone to deploy decentralized applications onto it, which anyone can then use.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) applications provide financial instruments that do not directly rely on financial intermediaries like brokerages, exchanges, or banks.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] This facilitates borrowing against cryptocurrency holdings or lending them out for interest.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Ethereum allows users to create fungible (e.g.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] ERC-20) and non-fungible tokens (NFTs) with a variety of properties, and to create smart contracts that can receive, hold and send those assets in accordance with the contract's immutable code and a transaction's input data.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] On 15 September 2022, Ethereum transitioned its consensus mechanism from proof-of-work (PoW) to proof-of-stake (PoS) in an update known as "The Merge", which cut the blockchain's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Ethereum was initially described in late 2013 in a white paper by Vitalik Buterin, a programmer and co-founder of *Bitcoin Magazine*, that described a way to build decentralized applications.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Buterin argued to the Bitcoin Core developers that blockchain technology could benefit from other applications besides money and that it needed a more robust language for application development that could lead to attaching real-world assets, such as stocks and property, to the blockchain.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In 2013, Buterin briefly worked with eToro CEO Yoni Assia on the Colored Coins project and drafted its white paper outlining additional use cases for blockchain technology.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] However, after failing to gain agreement on how the project should proceed, he proposed the development of a new platform with a more robust scripting language—a Turing-complete programming language—that would eventually become Ethereum.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Ethereum was announced at the North American Bitcoin Conference in Miami, in January 2014.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] During the conference, Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, and Anthony Di Iorio (who financed the project) rented a house in Miami with Buterin at which they could develop a fuller sense of what Ethereum might become.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Di Iorio invited friend Joseph Lubin, who invited reporter Morgen Peck, to bear witness.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Peck subsequently wrote about the experience in *Wired*.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Six months later the founders met again in Zug, Switzerland, where Buterin told the founders that the project would proceed as a non-profit.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Hoskinson left the project at that time and soon after founded IOHK, a blockchain company responsible for Cardano.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Ethereum has an unusually long list of founders.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Anthony Di Iorio wrote: "Ethereum was founded by Vitalik Buterin, Myself, Charles Hoskinson, Mihai Alisie & Amir Chetrit (the initial 5) in December 2013.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Joseph Lubin, Gavin Wood, & Jeffrey Wilcke were added in early 2014 as founders." Buterin chose the name Ethereum after browsing a list of elements from science fiction on Wikipedia.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Formal development of the software underlying Ethereum began in early 2014 through a Swiss company, Ethereum Switzerland GmbH (*EthSuisse*).The idea of putting executable smart contracts in the blockchain needed to be specified before it could be implemented in software.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] This work was done by Gavin Wood, then the chief technology officer, in the Ethereum Yellow Paper that specified the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Subsequently, a Swiss non-profit foundation, the **Ethereum Foundation** (*Stiftung Ethereum*), was founded.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Development was funded by an online public crowd sale from July to August 2014, in which participants bought the Ethereum value token (ether) with another digital currency, bitcoin.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] While there was early praise for the technical innovations of Ethereum, questions were also raised about its security and scalability.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The intended purpose of the three distinct implementations would be so that if one of them had a bug, the other two could be used as a comparison.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Several codenamed prototypes of Ethereum were developed over 18 months in 2014 and 2015 by the Ethereum Foundation as part of their proof-of-concept series.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] "Olympic" was the last prototype and public beta pre-release.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The Olympic network gave users a bug bounty of 25,000 ether for stress-testing the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] On 30 July 2015, "Frontier" marked the official launch of the Ethereum platform, and Ethereum created its "genesis block".
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The genesis block contained 8,893 transactions allocating various amounts of ether to different addresses, and a block reward of 5 ETH.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Since the initial launch, Ethereum has undergone a number of planned protocol upgrades, which are important changes affecting the underlying functionality and/or incentive structures of the platform.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Protocol upgrades are accomplished by means of a hard fork.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In 2016, a decentralized autonomous organization called The DAO—a set of smart contracts developed on the platform—raised a record US$150 million in a crowd sale to fund the project.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Emin Gün Sirer, Vlad Zamfir and Dino Mark had written a paper called *A Call for a Temporary Moratorium on The DAO* in which they described in which way the DAO might be vunerable to attacks.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The DAO was exploited in June 2016 when US$50 million of DAO tokens were stolen by an unknown hacker.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The event sparked a debate in the crypto-community about whether Ethereum should perform a contentious "hard fork" to reappropriate the affected funds.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The fork resulted in the network splitting into two blockchains: Ethereum with the theft reversed, and Ethereum Classic which continued on the original chain.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In March 2017, various blockchain startups, research groups, and *Fortune* 500 companies announced the creation of the Enterprise Ethereum Alliance (EEA) with 30 founding members.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] By May 2017, the nonprofit organization had 116 enterprise members, including ConsenSys, CME Group, Cornell University's research group, Toyota Research Institute, Samsung SDS, Microsoft, Intel, J.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Morgan, Cooley LLP, Merck KGaA, DTCC, Deloitte, Accenture, Banco Santander, BNY Mellon, ING, and National Bank of Canada.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] By July 2017, there were over 150 members in the alliance, including MasterCard, Cisco Systems, Sberbank, and Scotiabank.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In 2024, Paul Brody, EEA board member for EY, was announced as the new chairperson, and Karen Scarbrough, board member for Microsoft, as the new executive director.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Vanessa Grellet from Arche Capital also joined as a new board member.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In 2017, *CryptoKitties*, the blockchain game and decentralized application (dApp) featuring digital cat artwork as NFTs, was launched on the Ethereum network.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In cultivating popularity with users and collectors, it gained notable mainstream media attention providing significant exposure to Ethereum in the process.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] It was considered the most popular smart contract in use on the network but it also highlighted concerns over Ethereum's scalability due to the game's substantial consumption of network capacity at the time.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In January 2018, a community-driven paper (an EIP, "Ethereum Improvement Proposal") under the leadership of civic hacker and lead author William Entriken was published, called *ERC-721: Non-Fungible Token Standard.* It introduced ERC-721, the first official NFT standard on Ethereum.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] This standardization allowed Ethereum to become central to a multi-billion dollar digital collectibles market.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] By January 2018, ether was the second-largest cryptocurrency in terms of market capitalization, behind bitcoin.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] As of 2021, it maintained that relative position.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In 2019, Ethereum Foundation employee Virgil Griffith was arrested by the US government for presenting at a blockchain conference in North Korea.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] He would later plead guilty to one count of conspiring to violate the International Emergency Economic Powers Act in 2021.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In March 2021, Visa Inc. announced that it began settling stablecoin transactions using Ethereum.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In April 2021, JP Morgan Chase, UBS, and MasterCard announced that they were investing US$65 million into ConsenSys, a software development firm that builds Ethereum-related infrastructure.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] There were two network upgrades in 2021.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The first was "Berlin", implemented on 14 April 2021.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The second was "London", which took effect on 5 August.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The London upgrade included Ethereum Improvement Proposal ("EIP") 1559, a mechanism for reducing transaction fee volatility.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The mechanism causes a portion of the ether paid in transaction fees for each block to be destroyed rather than given to the block proposer, reducing the inflation rate of ether and potentially resulting in periods of deflation.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] On 27 August 2021, the blockchain experienced a brief fork that was the result of clients running different incompatible software versions.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] "The Merge" (formerly called Ethereum 2.0) was a set of three updates (Bellatrix, Paris, and Shapella) that transitioned Ethereum's consensus protocol from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Bellatrix updated the proof-of-stake Beacon chain and introduced economic slashing.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Paris was the event at block 15537393 on 15 September 2022 that merged Ethereum to the Beacon chain.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Shapella (Shanghai-Capella) was the update that allowed for staking withdrawals.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The switch from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake has cut Ethereum's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] However, the effect this has on global energy consumption and climate change may be limited since the computers previously used for mining ether may be used to mine other cryptocurrencies that are energy-intensive.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] On 13 March 2024, "Dencun" or also "Deneb-Cancun" set of upgrades went live.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] These included EIP-4844 (Proto-Danksharding) which introduced "blobs" that can be used for general-purpose data-availability.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Because "Blob" data is stored only temporarily, it is much cheaper than using normal call data for storage.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] This allows for Ethereum Layer 2 (L2) networks to greatly reduce the cost of posting compressed transaction data to the Layer 1 (L1).
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The Prague-Electra ("Pectra") update was launched on 7 May 2025.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The Fulu-Osaka update went live on 3 December 2025.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] This update introduced several protocol improvements.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Ethereum is a peer-to-peer network that maintains a database containing the storage values of all Ethereum accounts and processes state-altering transactions.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Approximately every 12 seconds, a batch of new transactions, known as a "block", is processed by the network.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Each block contains a cryptographic hash identifying the series of blocks that must precede it if the block is to be considered valid.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] This series of blocks is known as the blockchain.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Each "node" (network participant) connects with a relatively small subset of the network to offer blocks and unvalidated transactions (i.e. transactions not yet in the blockchain) to its peers for download, and it downloads any from its peers that it doesn't already have.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Each node usually has a unique set of peers, so that offering an item to its peers results in the propagation of that item throughout the entire network within seconds.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] A node's collection of unvalidated transactions is known as its "mempool".
[src:hardhat/ethereum] A node may choose to create a copy of the state for itself.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] It does this by starting with the genesis state and executing every transaction in the blockchain, in the proper order of blocks and in the order they are listed within each block.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may "stake" (deposit) 32 or more ETH to register a "validator".
[src:hardhat/ethereum] At the end of each "epoch" (32 block slots, each slot lasting 12 seconds), each validator is pseudorandomly assigned to one of the slots of the epoch after the next, either as the block proposer or as an attester.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] During a slot, the block proposer uses their mempool to create a block that is intended to become the new "head" (latest block) of the blockchain, and the attesters attest to which block is at the head of the chain.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] If a validator makes self-contradicting proposals or attestations, or if it is inactive, it loses a portion of its stake.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may send ETH to a validator at any time to increase its stake.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] A validator's attestation is given a weight equal to its stake or 2,048, whichever is less.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] According to the Ethereum protocol, the blockchain with the highest accumulated weight of attestations at any given time is to be regarded as the canonical chain.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Validators are rewarded for making valid proposals and attestations.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] A validator's rewards are paid via transactions within the same chain that contains their proposal or attestation, and therefore would have little or no market value unless that chain becomes the canonical chain.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] This incentivizes validators to support the chain that they think other validators view as the canonical chain, which results in a high degree of consensus.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Ether (ETH) is the cryptocurrency generated in accordance with the Ethereum protocol as a reward to validators in a proof-of-stake system for adding blocks to the blockchain.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Ether is represented in the state as an unsigned integer associated with each account, this being the account's ETH balance denominated in wei (1018 wei = 1 ether).
[src:hardhat/ethereum] At the end of each epoch, new ETH is generated by the addition of protocol-specified amounts to the balances of all validators that made valid block proposals or attestations in the epoch before the last (i.e. the epoch being finalized).
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Additionally, ether is the only currency accepted by the protocol as payment for the transaction fee.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The transaction fee is composed of two parts: the base fee and the tip.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The base fee is "burned" (deleted from existence) and the tip goes to the block proposer.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The validator reward together with the tips provide the incentive to validators to keep the blockchain growing (i.e. to keep processing new transactions).
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Therefore, ETH is fundamental to the operation of the network.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Ether may be "sent" from one account to another via a transaction, the execution of which simply entails subtracting the *amount to be sent* from the sender's balance and adding the same amount to the recipient's balance.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Ether is often erroneously referred to as "Ethereum".
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The uppercase Greek letter Xi, Ξ, is sometimes used as a currency symbol for ether.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] There are two types of accounts on Ethereum: user accounts (also known as externally-owned accounts), and contract accounts.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Both types have an ETH balance, may transfer ETH to any account, may execute the code of another contract, or create a new contract, and are identified on the blockchain and in the state by an account address.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Contracts are the only type of account that has associated bytecode and storage (to store contract-specific state).
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The code of a contract is evaluated when a transaction is sent to it.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The code of the contract may read user-specified data from the transaction, and may have a return value.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Ethereum account addresses are composed of the prefix "`0x`" (a common identifier for hexadecimal) concatenated with the rightmost 20 bytes of the Keccak-256 hash of the ECDSA public key (the curve used is the so-called *secp256k1*).
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In hexadecimal, two digits represent a byte, and so addresses contain 40 hexadecimal digits after the "`0x`", e.g.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Contract addresses are in the same format, however, they are determined by sender and creation transaction nonce.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) is the runtime environment for transaction execution in Ethereum.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The EVM is a stack based virtual machine with an instruction set specifically designed for Ethereum.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The instruction set includes, among other things, stack operations, memory operations, and operations to inspect the current execution context, such as remaining gas, information about the current block, and the current transaction.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The EVM is designed to be deterministic on a wide variety of hardware and operating systems, so that given a pre-transaction state and a transaction, each node produces the same post-transaction state, thereby enabling network consensus.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The formal definition of the EVM is specified in the Ethereum Yellow Paper.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] EVMs have been implemented in C++, C#, Go, Haskell, Java, JavaScript, Python, Ruby, Rust, Elixir, Erlang, and soon WebAssembly.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Gas is a unit of account within the EVM used in the calculation of the transaction fee, which is the amount of ETH a transaction's sender must pay to the network to have the transaction included in the blockchain.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Each type of operation which may be performed by the EVM is hardcoded with a certain gas cost, which is intended to be roughly proportional to the monetary value of the resources (e.g. computation and storage) a node must expend or dedicate to perform that operation.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] When a sender is creating a transaction, the sender must specify a *gas limit* and *gas price*.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The *gas limit* is the maximum amount of gas the sender is willing to use in the transaction, and the *gas price* is the amount of ETH the sender wishes to pay to the network per unit of gas used.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] A transaction may only be included in the blockchain at a block slot that has a *base gas price* less than or equal to the transaction's *gas price*.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The portion of the *gas price* that is in excess of the *base gas price* is known as the tip and goes to the block proposer; the higher the tip, the more incentive a block proposer has to include the transaction in their block, and thus the quicker the transaction will be included in the blockchain.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The sender buys the full amount of gas (i.e. their ETH balance is debited *gas limit* × *gas price* and their gas balance is set to *gas limit*) up-front, at the start of the execution of the transaction, and is refunded at the end for any unused gas.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] If at any point the transaction does not have enough gas to perform the next operation, the transaction is reverted but the sender is still only refunded for the unused gas.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In user interfaces, gas prices are typically denominated in gigawei (Gwei), a subunit of ETH equal to 10−9 ETH.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The EVM's instruction set is Turing-complete.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Ethereum's smart contracts are written in high-level programming languages and then compiled down to EVM bytecode, which is then deployed to the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] They can be written in Solidity (a language library with similarities to C and JavaScript), as well as others.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Source code and compiler information are usually published on blockchain explorer websites soon after the launch of the contract so that users can see the code and verify that it compiles to the bytecode that is on-chain.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] One issue related to using smart contracts on a public blockchain is that bugs, including security holes, are visible to all but cannot be fixed quickly.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] One example of this is the 2016 attack on The DAO, which could not be quickly stopped or reversed.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The ERC-20 (Ethereum Request-for-Comments #20) Token Standard allows for fungible tokens on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The standard, proposed by Fabian Vogelsteller in November 2015, implements an API for tokens within smart contracts.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The standard provides functions that include the transfer of tokens from one account to another, getting the current token balance of an account, and getting the total supply of the token available on the network.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Smart contracts that correctly implement ERC-20 processes are called ERC-20 Token Contracts, and they keep track of created tokens on Ethereum.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Numerous cryptocurrencies have launched as ERC-20 tokens and have been distributed through initial coin offerings.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Ethereum also allows for the creation of unique and indivisible tokens, called non-fungible tokens (NFTs).
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Since tokens of this type are unique, they have been used to represent such things as collectibles, digital art, sports memorabilia, virtual real estate, and items within games.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] ERC-721 is the first official NFT standard for Ethereum and was followed up by ERC-1155 which introduced semi-fungibility; both are widely used, though some fully fungible tokens using ERC-20 have been used for NFTs such as *CryptoPunks*.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The first NFT project, Etheria, a 3D map of tradable and customizable hexagonal tiles, was deployed to the network in October 2015 and demonstrated live at DEVCON1 in November of that year.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In 2021, Christie's sold a digital image with an NFT by Beeple for US$69.3 million, making him the third-most-valuable living artist in terms of auction prices at the time, although observers have noted that both the buyer and seller had a vested interest in driving demand for the artist's work.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) offers financial instruments in a decentralized architecture, outside of companies' and governments' control, such as money market funds which let users earn interest.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] DeFi applications are typically accessed through a Web3-enabled browser extension or application, such as MetaMask, which allows users to directly interact with the Ethereum blockchain through a website.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Many of these DApps can connect and work together to create complex financial services.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Examples of DeFi platforms include MakerDAO.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Uniswap, a decentralized exchange for tokens on Ethereum grew from US$20 million in liquidity to US$2.9 billion in 2020.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] As of October 2020, over US$11 billion was invested in various DeFi protocols.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Additionally, through a process called "wrapping", certain DeFi protocols allow synthetic versions of various assets (such as bitcoin, gold, and oil) to be tradeable on Ethereum and also compatible with all of Ethereum's major wallets and applications.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Aave is a protocol for microlending using Ethereum.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Ethereum-based software and networks, independent from the public Ethereum chain, have been tested by enterprise software companies.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Interested parties have included Microsoft, IBM, JPMorgan Chase, Deloitte, R3, and Innovate UK (cross-border payments prototype).
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Barclays, UBS, Credit Suisse, Amazon, Visa, and other companies have also experimented with Ethereum.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] As of December 2025, the maximum theoretical throughput for Ethereum L1 is 238 TPS (given its current 60M gas limit, 12s blocks, and 21k gas cost for ETH transfers).
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Due to large smart contract and batch transaction using more gas in each block, the average transaction throughput is much less.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] As of January 2016, the Ethereum averaged about 25 transactions per second; this did not change after the move to proof-of-stake.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In comparison, the Visa payment platform processes 45,000 payments per second.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] This has led some to question the scalability of Ethereum.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Ethereum's blockchain uses a Merkle–Patricia Tree to store account state in each block.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The trie allows for storage savings, set membership proofs (called "Merkle proofs"), and light client synchronization.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The network has faced congestion problems, such as in 2017 in relation to *CryptoKitties*.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Layer 2 (L2) is one of the approaches that the Ethereum ecosystem has developed in order to scale up and handle more transactions with lower transaction fees.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] A Layer 2 chain is a separate blockchain that extends Ethereum (Layer 1) and inherits the security guarantees of Ethereum.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] There are different types of L2 chains, including optimistic rollups and zero-knowledge rollups (zk rollups).
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Depending on their individual technical details, some L2 chains are capable of processing thousands of transactions per second.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The legal status of ether (ETH), Ethereum's native token, remains subject to uncertainty and varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In the United States, regulatory authorities have increasingly signaled that ether should be treated as a commodity under the jurisdiction of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC).
[src:hardhat/ethereum] The CFTC has repeatedly asserted its regulatory authority over Ethereum, with former CFTC Chairman Heath Tarbert stating in 2019 that "ETH is a commodity" and subsequent leadership maintaining this position.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] From a private law perspective, many jurisdictions have recognized ether as a form of intangible personal property that can be owned, transferred, and used as collateral, similar to other forms of personal property.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] In the United States specifically, the 2022 Amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property that includes digital assets like ether.
[src:hardhat/ethereum] Under UCC Article 12, ETH is classified as a CER, which provides a comprehensive framework for its commercial circulation.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] Hardhat 3 is stable and production ready, and teams are already migrating.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] Hardhat 2 will be upgraded to support the Glamsterdam hardfork and will continue to receive bug fixes and security fixes until its **end of life** — the earlier of the **Hegota mainnet activation** or the **1st of June 2027**.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] After that, there will be no further Hardhat 2 releases.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] Hardhat is a development environment for Ethereum software.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] It consists of different components for editing, compiling, debugging and deploying your smart contracts and dApps, all of which work together to create a complete development environment.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] Hardhat Runner is the main component you interact with when using Hardhat.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] It's a flexible and extensible task runner that helps you manage and automate the recurring tasks inherent to developing smart contracts and dApps.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] Hardhat Runner is designed around the concepts of **tasks** and **plugins**.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] Every time you're running Hardhat from the command-line, you're running a task.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] For example, `npx hardhat compile` runs the built-in `compile` task.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] Tasks can call other tasks, allowing complex workflows to be defined.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] Users and plugins can override existing tasks, making those workflows customizable and extendable.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] This guide will take you through the installation of our recommended setup, but as most of Hardhat's functionality comes from plugins, you are free to customize it or choose a completely different path.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] Hardhat for Visual Studio Code is the official Hardhat extension that adds advanced support for Solidity to VSCode.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] If you use Visual Studio Code, give it a try!
[src:hardhat/getting-started] Hardhat is used through a local installation in your project.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] This way your environment will be reproducible, and you will avoid future version conflicts.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] To install it, you need to create an npm project by going to an empty folder, running `npm init`, and following its instructions.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] You can use another package manager, like yarn, but we recommend you use npm 7 or later, as it makes installing Hardhat plugins simpler.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] To use your local installation of Hardhat, you need to use `npx` to run it (i.e.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] If you are using Windows, we **strongly recommend** using WSL 2 to follow this guide.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] We will explore the basics of creating a Hardhat project with a sample contract, tests of that contract, and a Hardhat Ignition module to deploy it.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] Let's create the JavaScript or TypeScript project and go through these steps to compile, test and deploy the sample contract.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] We recommend using TypeScript, but if you are not familiar with it just pick JavaScript.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] The list of available tasks includes the built-in ones and also those that came with any installed plugins.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] `npx hardhat` is your starting point to find out what tasks are available to run.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] If you created a TypeScript project, this task will also generate TypeScript bindings using TypeChain.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] Your project comes with tests that use Mocha, Chai, Ethers.js and Hardhat Ignition.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] Next, to deploy the contract we will use a Hardhat Ignition module.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] To learn more check out the Hardhat Ignition documentation.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] By default, Hardhat will spin up a new in-memory instance of Hardhat Network on startup.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] It's also possible to run Hardhat Network in a standalone fashion so that external clients can connect to it.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] This could be a wallet, your Dapp front-end, or a Hardhat Ignition deployment.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] This will expose a JSON-RPC interface to Hardhat Network.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] To use it connect your wallet or application to `http://127.0.0.1:8545`.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] If you want to connect Hardhat to this node, for example to run a deployment against it, you simply need to run it using `--network localhost`.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] To run Hardhat Network on specific port and allow incoming requests from a specific network interface or hostname, run `npx hardhat node --hostname 127.0.0.1 --port 8545`.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] If you want to allow incoming requests from anywhere, including external ips, use `--hostname 0.0.0.0`.
[src:hardhat/getting-started] You have created a project and compiled, tested and deployed a smart contract.
[src:hardhat/guides-deploying] To deploy your contracts, you can use Hardhat Ignition, our declarative deployment system.
[src:hardhat/guides-deploying] You can deploy the `Lock` contract from the sample project by using its accompanying Ignition module.
[src:hardhat/guides-deploying] An Ignition module is a TypeScript or JavaScript file that allows you to specify what needs to be deployed.
[src:hardhat/guides-deploying] If no network is specified, Hardhat Ignition will run against an in-memory instance of Hardhat Network.
[src:hardhat/guides-deploying] In the sample `LockModule` above, two module parameters are used: `unlockTime` which will default to the 1st of Jan 2030 and `lockedAmount` which will default to one Gwei.
[src:hardhat/guides-deploying] You can learn more about overriding these values by providing your own module parameters during deployment in our Deploying a module guide.
[src:hardhat/guides-deploying] Read more about Hardhat Ignition generally in the Hardhat Ignition documentation.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js allows developers to use JavaScript for writing command line tools and server-side scripting.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Running Javascript on the server is commonly used to generate dynamic web page content before the page is sent to the user's web browser.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Consequently, Node.js represents a "JavaScript everywhere" paradigm, unifying web-application development around a single programming language, as opposed to using different languages for the server- versus client-side programming.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js has an event-driven architecture capable of asynchronous I/O.
[src:hardhat/node-js] These design choices aim to optimize throughput and scalability in web applications with many input/output operations, as well as for real-time Web applications (e.g., real-time communication programs and browser games).
[src:hardhat/node-js] The Node.js distributed development project was previously governed by the Node.js Foundation, and has now merged with the JS Foundation to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:hardhat/node-js] OpenJS Foundation is facilitated by the Linux Foundation's Collaborative Projects program.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js was initially written by Ryan Dahl in 2009, about 13 years after the introduction of the first server-side JavaScript environment, Netscape's LiveWire Pro Web.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The initial release supported only Linux and Mac OS X.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Its development and maintenance was led by Dahl and later sponsored by Joyent.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Dahl demonstrated the project at the inaugural European JSConf on November 8, 2009.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js combined Google's V8 JavaScript engine, an event loop, and a low-level I/O API.
[src:hardhat/node-js] In January 2010, a package manager was introduced for the Node.js environment called npm.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The package manager allows programmers to publish and share Node.js packages, along with the accompanying source code, and is designed to simplify the installation, update and uninstallation of packages.
[src:hardhat/node-js] In June 2011, Microsoft and Joyent implemented a native Windows version of Node.js.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The first Node.js build supporting Windows was released in July 2011.
[src:hardhat/node-js] In January 2012, Dahl yielded management of the project to npm creator Isaac Schlueter.
[src:hardhat/node-js] In January 2014, Schlueter announced that Timothy J.
[src:hardhat/node-js] In December 2014, Fedor Indutny created io.js, a fork of Node.js created because of dissatisfaction with Joyent's governance as an open-governance alternative with a separate technical committee.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The goal was to enable a structure that would be more receptive to community input, including the updating of io.js with the latest Google V8 JavaScript engine releases, diverging from Node.js's approach at that time.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The Node.js Foundation, formed to reconcile Node.js and io.js under a unified banner, was announced in February 2015.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The merger was realized in September 2015 with Node.js v0.12 and io.js v3.3 combining into Node v4.0.
[src:hardhat/node-js] This merge brought V8 ES6 features into Node.js and started a long-term support release cycle.
[src:hardhat/node-js] By 2016, the io.js website recommended returning to Node.js and announced no further io.js releases, effectively ending the fork and solidifying the merger's success.
[src:hardhat/node-js] In 2019, the JS Foundation and Node.js Foundation merged to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The Node.js logo features a green hexagon with overlapping bands to represent the cross-platform nature of the runtime.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The Rocket Turtle was chosen as the official Node.js mascot in February 2024 following a design contest.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js allows the creation of web servers and networking tools using JavaScript and a collection of "modules" that handle various core functionalities.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Modules are provided for file system I/O, networking (DNS, HTTP, TCP, TLS/SSL or UDP), binary data (buffers), cryptography functions, data streams and other core functions.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js's modules use an API designed to reduce the complexity of writing server applications.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Since version 22.6.0, Node.js natively supports both JavaScript and TypeScript, allowing TypeScript files to be executed without a separate compilation step.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The TypeScript support was contributed by Node.js TSC member Marco Ippolito.
[src:hardhat/node-js] In addition, many compile-to-JS languages are available, allowing Node.js applications to also be written in CoffeeScript, Dart, ClojureScript, and others.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js is primarily used to build network programs such as web servers.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The most significant difference between Node.js and PHP is that most functions in PHP block until completion (commands execute only after previous commands finish), while Node.js functions are non-blocking (commands execute concurrently and use callbacks to signal completion or failure).
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js is officially supported by Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows 8.1 and Server 2012 (and later), with Tier 2 support for SmartOS and IBM AIX and experimental support for FreeBSD.
[src:hardhat/node-js] OpenBSD also works, and LTS versions are available for IBM i (AS/400).
[src:hardhat/node-js] The source code may also be built on similar operating systems that are not officially supported, such as NonStop OS and Unix servers.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js enables development of fast web servers in JavaScript using event-driven programming.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Developers can create scalable servers without using threading by using a simplified model that uses callbacks to signal the completion of a task.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js connects the ease of a scripting language (JavaScript) with the power of Unix network programming.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js was built on top of Google's V8 JavaScript engine since it was open-sourced under the BSD license, and it contains comprehensive support for fundamental protocols such as HTTP, DNS and TCP.
[src:hardhat/node-js] JavaScript's existing popularity made Node.js accessible to the web-development community.
[src:hardhat/node-js] There are thousands of open-source libraries for Node.js, most of which are hosted on the npm website.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Multiple developer conferences and events are held that support the Node.js community, including NodeConf, Node Interactive, and Node Summit, as well as a number of regional events.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The open-source community has developed web frameworks to accelerate the development of applications.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Such frameworks include Express.js, Socket.IO, Sails.js, Next.js and Meteor.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Various packages have also been created for interfacing with other languages or runtime environments such as Microsoft .NET.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Modern desktop IDEs provide editing and debugging features specifically for Node.js applications.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Such IDEs include Atom, Brackets, JetBrains WebStorm, Microsoft Visual Studio (with Node.js Tools for Visual Studio, or TypeScript with Node definitions), NetBeans, Nodeclipse Enide Studio (Eclipse-based) and Visual Studio Code.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Some online IDEs also support Node.js, such as Codeanywhere, Eclipse Che, Cloud9 IDE and the visual flow editor in Node-RED.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js is supported across a number of cloud-hosting platforms such as Jelastic, Google Cloud Platform, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Azure Web Apps and Joyent.
[src:hardhat/node-js] New major releases of Node.js are cut from the GitHub main branch every six months.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Even-numbered versions are cut in April and odd-numbered versions are cut in October.
[src:hardhat/node-js] When a new odd version is released, the previous even version undergoes transition to Long Term Support (LTS), which gives that version 12 months of active support from the date it is designated LTS.
[src:hardhat/node-js] After these 12 months expire, an LTS release receives an additional 18 months of maintenance support.
[src:hardhat/node-js] An active version receives non-breaking backports of changes a few weeks after they land in the current release.
[src:hardhat/node-js] A maintenance release receives only critical fixes and documentation updates.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The LTS Working Group manages strategy and policy in collaboration with the Technical Steering Committee of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that processes incoming requests in a loop, called the event loop.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js uses libuv under the hood to handle asynchronous events.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Libuv is an abstraction layer for network and file system functionality on both Windows and POSIX-based systems such as Linux, macOS, OSS on NonStop, and Unix.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js relies on nghttp2 for HTTP support.
[src:hardhat/node-js] As of version 20, Node.js uses the ada library which provides up-to-date WHATWG URL compliance.
[src:hardhat/node-js] As of version 19.5, Node.js uses the simdutf library for fast Unicode validation and transcoding.
[src:hardhat/node-js] As of version 21.3, Node.js uses the simdjson library for fast JSON parsing.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js operates on a single-thread event loop, using non-blocking I/O calls, allowing it to support tens of thousands of concurrent connections without incurring the cost of thread context switching.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The design of sharing a single thread among all the requests that use the observer pattern is intended for building highly concurrent applications, where any function performing I/O must use a callback.
[src:hardhat/node-js] To accommodate the single-threaded event loop, Node.js uses the libuv library—which, in turn, uses a fixed-sized thread pool that handles some of the non-blocking asynchronous I/O operations.
[src:hardhat/node-js] A thread pool handles the execution of parallel tasks in Node.js.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The main thread function call posts tasks to the shared task queue, which threads in the thread pool pull and execute.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Inherently non-blocking system functions such as networking translate to kernel-side non-blocking sockets, while inherently blocking system functions such as file I/O run in a blocking way on their own threads.
[src:hardhat/node-js] When a thread in the thread pool completes a task, it informs the main thread of this, which in turn, wakes up and executes the registered callback.
[src:hardhat/node-js] A downside of this single-threaded approach is that Node.js does not allow vertical scaling by increasing the number of CPU cores of the machine it is running on without using an additional module, such as cluster, StrongLoop Process Manager, or pm2.
[src:hardhat/node-js] However, developers can increase the default number of threads in the libuv thread pool.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The server operating system (OS) is likely to distribute these threads across multiple cores.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Another problem is that long-lasting computations and other CPU-bound tasks freeze the entire event-loop until completion.
[src:hardhat/node-js] V8 is the JavaScript execution engine which was initially built for Google Chrome.
[src:hardhat/node-js] It was then open-sourced by Google in 2008.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Written in C++, V8 compiles JavaScript source code to native machine code at runtime.
[src:hardhat/node-js] As of 2016, it also includes Ignition, a bytecode interpreter.
[src:hardhat/node-js] npm is the pre-installed package manager for the Node.js server platform.
[src:hardhat/node-js] It installs Node.js programs from the npm registry, organizing the installation and management of third-party Node.js programs.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js registers with the operating system so the OS notifies it of asynchronous I/O events such as new connections.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Within the Node.js runtime, events trigger callbacks and each connection is handled as a small heap allocation.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Traditionally, relatively heavyweight OS processes or threads handled each connection.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js uses an event loop for concurrent I/O, instead of processes or threads.
[src:hardhat/node-js] In contrast to other event-driven servers, Node.js's event loop does not need to be called explicitly.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Instead, callbacks are defined, and the server automatically enters the event loop at the end of the callback definition.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js exits the event loop when there are no further callbacks to be performed.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js supports WebAssembly and as of Node 14 has experimental support of WASI, the WebAssembly System Interface.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Node.js provides a way to create "add-ons" via a C-based API called N-API, which can be used to produce loadable (importable) `.node` modules from source code written in C/C++.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The modules can be directly loaded into memory and executed from within JS environment as simple CommonJS modules.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The implementation of the N-API relies on internal C/C++ Node.js and V8 objects requiring users to import (#include) Node.js specific headers into their native source code.
[src:hardhat/node-js] As the Node.js API is subject to breaking changes at a binary level, modules have to be built and shipped against specific Node.js versions to work properly.
[src:hardhat/node-js] To address the issue, third parties have introduced open-sourced С/С++ wrappers on top of the API that partially alleviate the problem.
[src:hardhat/node-js] They simplify interfaces, but as a side effect they may also introduce complexity which maintainers have to deal with.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Even though the core functionality of Node.js resides in a JavaScript built-in library, modules written in C++ can be used to enhance capabilities and to improve performance of applications.
[src:hardhat/node-js] In order to produce such modules one needs to have an appropriate C++ compiler and necessary headers (the latter are typically shipped with Node.js itself), e.g., gcc, clang or MSVC++.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The N-API is similar to Java Native Interface.
[src:hardhat/node-js] OpenHarmony and ArkTS also adopts N-API, with the internal implementation rewritten.
[src:hardhat/node-js] In 2015, various branches of the greater Node.js community began working under the vendor-neutral Node.js Foundation.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The Node.js Foundation Technical Steering Committee (TSC) is the technical governing body of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The TSC is responsible for the core Node.js repo as well as dependent and adjacent projects.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Generally the TSC delegates the administration of these projects to working groups or committees.
[src:hardhat/node-js] The LTS group that manages long term supported releases is one such group.
[src:hardhat/node-js] Other current groups include Website, Streams, Build, Diagnostics, i18n, Evangelism, Docker, Addon API, Benchmarking, Post-mortem, Intl, Documentation, and Testing.
[src:hardhat/node-js] In August 2017, a third of the TSC members resigned due to a dispute related to the project's code of conduct.
[src:hardhat/node-js] They resigned after a vote failed to remove a member from the leadership group against whom multiple complaints had been filed.
[src:hardhat/project-setup] Hardhat projects are Node.js projects with the `hardhat` package installed and a `hardhat.config.js` file.
[src:hardhat/project-setup] To initialize a Node.js project you can use npm or yarn.
[src:hardhat/project-setup] And this is enough to run Hardhat using a default project structure.
[src:hardhat/project-setup] If you select *Create a JavaScript project*, a simple project creation wizard will ask you some questions.
[src:hardhat/project-setup] After that, the wizard will create some directories and files and install the necessary dependencies.
[src:hardhat/project-setup] The most important of these dependencies is the Hardhat Toolbox, a plugin that bundles all the things you need to start working with Hardhat.
[src:hardhat/project-setup] These are the default paths for a Hardhat project.
[src:hardhat/project-setup] If you need to change these paths, take a look at the paths configuration section.
[src:hardhat/project-setup] You can learn more about this in the Testing contracts guide.
[src:hardhat/project-setup] If you need to use an external network, like an Ethereum testnet, mainnet or some other specific node software, you can set it up using the `networks` configuration entries in the exported object in `hardhat.config.js`, which is how Hardhat projects manage settings.
[src:hardhat/project-setup] You can make use of the `--network` CLI parameter to quickly change the network.
[src:hardhat/project-setup] Take a look at the networks configuration section to learn more about setting up different networks.
[src:hardhat/project-setup] Most of Hardhat's functionality comes from plugins, so check out the plugins section for the official list and see if there are any ones of interest to you.
[src:hardhat/project-setup] Plugins are **essential** to Hardhat projects, so make sure to check out all the available ones and also build your own!
[src:hardhat/solidity] Solidity was proposed in August 2014 by Gavin Wood The language was later developed by the Ethereum project's Solidity team, led by Christian Reitwiessner.
[src:hardhat/solidity] Solidity is the primary language used to develop smart contracts for Ethereum and other private blockchains, such as the enterprise-oriented Hyperledger Fabric blockchain.
[src:hardhat/solidity] SWIFT deployed a proof of concept using Solidity running on Hyperledger Fabric.
[src:hardhat/solidity] Solidity is a statically typed programming language designed for developing smart contracts that run on the Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) or compatible virtual machines.
[src:hardhat/solidity] Solidity uses ECMAScript-like syntax which makes it familiar for web developers; however unlike ECMAScript it has static typing and variadic return types.
[src:hardhat/solidity] Solidity is different from other EVM-targeting languages such as Serpent and Mutan in some important ways.
[src:hardhat/solidity] It supports complex member variables for smart contracts, including arbitrarily hierarchical mappings and structs.
[src:hardhat/solidity] Solidity smart contract support inheritance, including multiple inheritance with C3 linearization.
[src:hardhat/solidity] Solidity introduces an application binary interface (ABI) that facilitates multiple type-safe functions within one smart contract (this was also later supported by Serpent).
[src:hardhat/solidity] The Solidity proposal also includes "Natural Language Specification", a documentation system for specifying user-centric descriptions of the ramifications of method-calls.
[src:hardhat/solidity] Many security properties of smart contracts are inherently difficult to reason about directly, and the Turing-completeness of Solidity means that verification of arbitrary properties cannot be decidably automated.
[src:hardhat/solidity] Current automated solutions for smart contract security analysis can miss critical violations, produce false positives, and fail to achieve sufficient code coverage on realistic contracts.
[src:hardhat/solidity] Solidity has been blamed for the error-prone implementation of Ethereum smart contracts due to its counterintuitive nature, its lack of constructs to deal with blockchain domain-specific aspects, and its lack of centralized documentation of known vulnerabilities.
[src:hardhat/solidity] In 2016, a Cornell University researcher stated that Solidity was partly to blame for The DAO hack that occurred that year.
[src:hardhat/solidity] The developers community often cites Solidity requiring much of third party interfaces and APIs, and its inability to create critical information intensive smart contracts.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] After compiling your contracts, the next step is to write some tests to verify that they work as intended.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] This guide explains our recommended approach for testing contracts in Hardhat.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] It relies on ethers to connect to Hardhat Network and on Mocha and Chai for the tests.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] It also uses our custom Chai matchers and our Hardhat Network Helpers to make it easier to write clean test code.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] These packages are part of the Hardhat Toolbox plugin; if you followed the previous guides, you should already have them installed.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] While this is our recommended test setup, Hardhat is flexible: you can customize the approach or take a completely different path with other tools.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] In this guide we'll write some tests for the sample project.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] If you haven't done it yet, go and initialize it.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] We recommend you use TypeScript to get better autocompletion and catch possible errors earlier.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] This guide will assume you are using TypeScript, but you can click the tabs of the code examples to see the Javascript counterpart.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] The setup includes some example tests in the `test/Lock.ts` file, but ignore them for now.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] Instead, create a `test/my-tests.ts` file.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] During this guide we'll only run those, by running `npx hardhat test test/my-tests.ts`, instead of just `npx hardhat test`.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] In the following sections we'll write some tests for the `Lock` contract that comes with the sample project.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] If you haven't read it yet, please take a look at the `contracts/Lock.sol` file.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] First we import the things we are going to use: the `expect` function from `chai` to write our assertions, the Hardhat Runtime Environment (`hre`), and the network helpers to interact with the Hardhat Network.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] After that we use the `describe` and `it` functions, which are global Mocha functions used to describe and group your tests.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] The test itself is what's inside the callback argument to the `it` function.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] First we set the values for the amount we want to lock (in wei) and the unlock time.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] For the latter we use `time.latest`, a network helper that returns the timestamp of the last mined block.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] Then we deploy the contract itself: we call `ethers.deployContract` with the name of the contract we want to deploy and an array of constructor arguments that has the unlock time.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] We also pass an object with the transaction parameters.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] This is optional, but we'll use it to send some ETH by setting its `value` field.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] Finally, we check that the value returned by the `unlockTime()` getter in the contract matches the value that we used when we deployed it.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] Since all the functions on a contract are async, we have to use the `await` keyword to get its value; otherwise, we would be comparing a promise with a number and this would always fail.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] In the previous test we checked that a getter function returned the correct value.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] This was a read-only function that can be called without paying a fee and without any risk.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] Other functions, however, can modify the state of the contract, like the `withdraw` function in the `Lock` contract.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] This means that we want some pre-conditions to be met for this function to be called successfully.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] The first statement checks that the unlock time has been reached, and the second one checks that the address calling the contract is its owner.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] In the previous test we used `.to.equal`, which is part of Chai and is used to compare two values.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] Here we are using `.to.be.revertedWith`, which asserts that a transaction reverts, and that the reason string of the revert is equal to the given string.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] The `.to.be.revertedWith` matcher is not part of Chai itself; instead, it's added by the Hardhat Chai Matchers plugin, which is included in the sample project we are using.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] Notice that in the previous test we wrote `expect(await ...)` but now we are doing `await expect(...)`.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] In the first case we were comparing two values in a synchronous way; the inner await is just there to wait for the value to be retrieved.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] In the second case, the whole assertion is async because it has to wait until the transaction is mined.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] This means that the `expect` call returns a promise that we have to await.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] We are deploying our `Lock` contract with an unlock time of one year.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] If we want to write a test that checks what happens after the unlock time has passed, we can't wait that amount of time.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] We could use a shorter unlock time, like 5 seconds, but that's a less realistic value and it's still a long time to wait in a test.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] The solution is to simulate the passage of time.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] As we mentioned, calling `lock.withdraw()` returns a Promise.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] If the transaction fails, the promise will be rejected.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] Using `await` will throw in that case, so the test will fail if the transaction reverts.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] The second check done by the `withdraw` function is that the function was called by the owner of the contract.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] By default, deployments and function calls are done with the first configured account.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] If we want to check that only the owner can call some function, we need to use a different account and verify that it fails.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] The `ethers.getSigners()` returns an array with all the configured accounts.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] Here again we are calling a function and asserting that it reverts with the correct reason string.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] The difference is that we are using `.connect(anotherAccount)` to call the method from a different address.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] So far we've deployed the `Lock` contract in each test.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] This means that at the beginning of each test we have to get the contract factory and then deploy the contract.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] This might be fine for a single contract but, if you have a more complicated setup, each test will have several lines at the beginning just to set up the desired state, and most of the time these lines will be the same.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] The `loadFixture` helper in the Hardhat Network Helpers fixes both of these problems.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] This helper receives a *fixture*, a function that sets up the chain to some desired state.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] The first time `loadFixture` is called, the fixture is executed.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] But the second time, instead of executing the fixture again, `loadFixture` will reset the state of the network to the point where it was right after the fixture was executed.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] This is faster, and it undoes any state changes done by the previous test.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] The fixture function can return anything you want, and the `loadFixture` helper will return it.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] We recommend returning an object like we did here, so you can extract only the values you care about for that test.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] There are several other things you can test, like which events are emitted or how the balances of the involved addresses change.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] Check the `test/Lock.ts` file to see the other examples.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] The Hardhat Toolbox includes the `solidity-coverage` plugin to measure the test coverage in your project.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] The Hardhat Toolbox also includes the `hardhat-gas-reporter` plugin to get metrics of how much gas is used, based on the execution of your tests.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] Alternatively, use `parallel: true` in the `mocha` section of your Hardhat config.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] There are some other limitations related to parallel mode.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] You can read more about them in Mocha's docs.
[src:hardhat/test-contracts] And if you are running into some issue when using parallel mode, you can check their Troubleshooting parallel mode section.
